{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/41069.Stand_on_Zanzibar", "title": "Stand on Zanzibar", "titleComplete": "Stand on Zanzibar", "description": "Norman Niblock House is a rising executive at General Technics, one of a few all-powerful corporations. His work is leading General Technics to the forefront of global domination, both in the marketplace and politically\u2014it's about to take over a country in Africa. Donald Hogan is his roommate, a seemingly sheepish bookworm. But Hogan is a spy, and he's about to discover a breakthrough in genetic engineering that will change the world ... and kill him. These two men's lives weave through one of science fiction's most praised novels. Written in a way that echoes John Dos Passos' U.S.A. Trilogy, Stand on Zanzibar is a cross-section of a world overpopulated by the billions. Where society is squeezed into hive-living madness by god-like mega computers, mass-marketed psychedelic drugs, and mundane uses of genetic engineering. Though written in 1968, it speaks of 2010, and is frighteningly prescient and intensely powerful.This edition comes with a tipped in collectors' note and an introduction by David Brin.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1360613921i/41069.jpg", "genres": ["Science Fiction Fantasy", "Speculative Fiction", "Cyberpunk", "Novels", "Hugo Awards", "Fiction", "Classics", "Dystopia", "Fantasy", "Science Fiction"], "asin": "1857988361", "isbn": "1857988361", "isbn13": "9781857988369", "publisher": "Gollancz", "author": ["John Brunner"], "publishDate": 934441200000, "ratingHistogram": [490, 1056, 3336, 5700, 5871], "ratingsCount": 16453, "reviewsCount": 784, "numPages": 672, "language": "English", "awards": [{"name": "Hugo Award", "awardedAt": -31507200000, "category": "Best Novel", "hasWon": null}, {"name": "Nebula Award", "awardedAt": -63129600000, "category": "Best Novel", "hasWon": null}, {"name": "British Science Fiction Association A